      "summary": "New pre-flight spec gate requires a literal 'Requirements' heading, rejecting otherwise-valid specs",
      "evidence": "ctx = gates.check_context(\"spec\", spec_text) at scripts/adversarial_plan.py:234 uses the 'spec' threshold profile in adversarial_common/gates.py:20, which sets required_sections=[\"Requirements\"]. check_context (gates.py:57-63) fails the whole run with EXIT_USAGE unless the spec contains a heading/line whose casefolded text is exactly 'Requirements' (not a substring match, e.g. 'Functional Requirements', 'Acceptance Criteria', or 'Goals' would NOT match). This is a new hard gate on real user-supplied spec.md files (adversarial_plan.py's stated purpose per its module docstring is to plan from an arbitrary spec.md); any spec that doesn't happen to use that exact heading name is now rejected before git setup even runs, even though it previously worked. The only reason existing tests still pass is that tests/conftest.py's VALID_SPEC fixture happens to already contain a '## Requirements' heading (conftest.py:29) \u2014 that fixture predates this diff and was not written to validate this new gate.",
